        followup: "Those three heart attacks mattered. Including them would have changed the safety signal from 'possibly concerning' to 'clearly dangerous.' Instead, the published paper suggested the increased heart attacks might be because the comparison drug (naproxen) was protective—not because Vioxx was deadly. The NEJM editors only learned of the missing data years later. They published an 'expression of concern,' calling it 'inaccurate and incomplete.' By then, tens of thousands had suffered heart attacks. The data cutoff wasn't a scientific decision. It was a marketing decision disguised as methodology."
